# **Evolutionary Dead-end vs. Megadiversity: Genomic Insights into the *Begoniaceae* Lineages**

# **Aim**

This project aims to uncover the genetic factors driving the contrasting evolutionary trajectories of the pan-tropical *Begonia* and monotypic *Hillebrandia* genus within the *Begoniaceae* family. Using whole-genome sequencing and population- and phyllo- genomics analyses, we will investigate whether differences in deleterious mutations, gene duplications, or transposable element activity explain this disparity. The findings will provide insights into speciation, adaptation, and extinction risk, with direct applications for conservation genomics and genetic rescue strategies.

# **Background**

An enduring enigma in evolutionary biology is the existence of megadiverse and depauperate sister lineages, which may provide insights into the factors shaping biodiversity. The *Begoniaceae* Family *Cucurbitales* is marked by a significant disparity: while the genus *Begonia* L. boasts 2,151 species distributed globally in the tropics, *Hillebrandia* Oliv. is a monotypic genus, represented by a single species, *Hillebrandia sandwicensis*, confined to a few islands in the Hawaiian archipelago. Despite both genera sharing a common ancestor only \~ 24.6 million years ago [(Moonlight *et al.*, 2018\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?4KtJGt) *Begonia* has diversified rapidly, adapting to various environmental niches, and radiating into a diversity of forms and life strategies, including narrow endemics and widespread weedy species [(Brennan *et al.*, 2012; Li *et al.*, 2022\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?uwLrTb). In contrast, *Hillebrandia* is limited to small, isolated populations in Hawaii [(MacCaughey, 1918; Clement *et al.*, 2004; Moonlight *et al.*, 2018\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?Rx9TbE). Genomic analysis of *Begonia* has shown that its species richness may be linked to a highly dynamic genome due to many Transposable Elements (TEs) [(Campos-Dominguez *et al.*, 2022; Li *et al.*, 2022; Chen *et al.*, 2024\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?pug1t1). However, it remains unclear why *Hillebrandia* did not diversify in an analogous way, even across the different islands of the Hawaiian archipelago, despite sharing strong genetic similarities with *Begonia* [(Campos-Dominguez *et al.*, 2022\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?v7J0Lv).

*Begonia* is a pan-tropical genus of monoecious perennial herbs, shrubs, and lianas. While some species exhibit high levels of selfing [(Agren’ and Schemske, 1993\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?BP75mB), others, like *B. kaniensis*, employ strategies such as asynchronous flowering (dichogamy) to prevent self-fertilization [(Wilson *et al.*, 2020\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?S7E9NZ), resulting in a mix of selfing and outcrossing across the genus. It is one of the most species-rich genera with a pan-tropical distribution and is known for its large diversity of morphologies [(Forrest, 2000; Plana, 2003; Neale, Goodall-Copestake and Kidner, 2006](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?8f3YZs), Fig.1). However, *Begonia*'s typical population has a restricted distribution on a local scale. Many species form narrow endemic populations with limited pollen dispersal and are genetically isolated [(Matolweni, Balkwill and McLellan, 2000; Hughes, Russell and Hollingsworth, 2002\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?yJKuZu).  
*Hillebrandia* is a monoecious, perennial, herbaceous flowering plant. While its mating system has not been thoroughly studied, the observed lower levels of heterozygosity than for *Begonia*  indicate that self-pollination likely plays a significant role in the species. [(Campos-Domınguez, 2022\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?bq67o7). It is endemic to the Hawaiian Archipelago, specifically found on the islands of Kauai, Maui, and Molokai. Although it was once reported on Oahu, it is now believed to be extinct on that island. [(Daniel, 1865](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?hUOqHU), [Clement *et al.*, 2004\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?gg1w0A). The species is more abundant on Kauai and Maui, but its populations are becoming increasingly rare [(Lorence, D. H., 1987\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?FlOyoT). The populations are confined to wet ravines and montane rainforests, and are rare and localized ([MacCaughey, 1918\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?o7qQt8), even though other seemingly suitable habitats exist within their range ([Clement *et al.*, 2004](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?yR7VsK)).

# **Project plan**

### **Research questions**

We question why *Begonia* has diversified, while *Hillebrandia* has not?

A first hypothesis would be that *Hillebrandia* has accumulated a higher number of rare, high-impact deleterious alleles compared to *Begonia*, limiting *Hillebrandia*’s capacity to diversify, while still maintaining viability, as it has already been observed in the *Begonia masoniana* species complex [(Chen *et al.*, 2024\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?73UBkv).

A second hypothesis is that gene duplications in *Begonia* provided diversification advantages or shielded the genus against harmful mutations by preserving multiple copies of highly conserved genes as backup compensation [(Ihmels *et al.*, 2007; Kuzmin, Taylor and Boone, 2022\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?VDsdtW).

A third hypothesis is that TEs are less active in *Hillebrandia*, resulting in lower genetic variation and hindering its diversification [(Campos-Dominguez *et al.*, 2022\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?0cLuRP).

Addressing these questions could reveal how genetic architecture influences adaptation, speciation, and extinction risk. Furthermore, no detailed population genetics studies have been conducted on *Hillebrandia*. Its degree of endemism, dispersion patterns across the islands, and potential for introgression remain unknown. A detailed study of the intraspecific genetic structure and genetic load within these populations is essential to assess genomic divergence between populations and to estimate the species conservation status, providing guidance for further actions to preserve this relict species. Additionally, it will fill gaps in knowledge regarding the species ploidy level and mating system.

To achieve this, we will characterise genetic variation in all its components, from single nucleotide polymorphism (SNPs) to large scale structural variations (SVs). We will then classify the mutations according to their predicted phenotypic effect (i.e. deleterious, neutral, advantageous) to uncover the evolutionary changes that contributed to the differences in diversification between the two genera. Building on these foundations, we can leverage these data to develop highly impactful conservation genomics strategies.

### **Experiment design**

For the required genomic analysis, we will conduct whole-genome sequencing on 20 selected *Begonia* and *Hillebrandia* accessions (Illumina, paired-end short reads, \~20× targeted coverage) to detect deleterious alleles and study genomic structure. Additionally, we will perform whole-genome sequencing on 80 *Hillebrandia* accessions (Illumina, paired-end short reads, \~10× targeted coverage) for population genetic studies. We will then map the illumina reads on the pre-existing high-quality reference *Begonia* genomes produced by [Li *et al.*, 2022](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?C338JA), as well as the *Begonia* and *Hillebrandia* genome accessible from RBGE (Table 1).   
To test our first hypothesis, we will identify highly conserved alleles across a diverse range of Begonia species, representing major clades within the genus (Fig. 1), and in *Hillebrandia* populations. We will then examine the number, type, and distribution of fitness effects of the various alleles and compare them between the two genera [(Long *et al.*, 2023\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?nl2y7F). In parallel, population genetics analyses will be conducted to infer current effective population sizes and past demographic changes in *Hillebrandia* populations, helping to identify the factors that contributed to the higher accumulation of deleterious mutations in *Hillebrandia* compared to *Begonia* [(Baumdicker *et al.*, 2022; Marchi, Kapopoulou and Excoffier, 2024\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?nb6epd).

To test the second hypothesis, we will use the method developed in the Milesi laboratory to accurately call SVs from short Illumina read datasets (Zhou et al. *in prep.*). This approach will reveal what structural genomic changes (e.g., insertions, duplications, inversions) may have contributed to the distinct evolutionary paths of the two genera [(Mahmoud *et al.*, 2019; Cochetel *et al.*, 2023\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?AcxKr7). 

We will use the same dataset to test our third hypothesis by detecting TEs, identifying TEs insertion polymorphisms, and estimating their contribution to genetic diversity in both genera [(Wendel *et al.*, 2016; Klein and O’Neill, 2018\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?ohCFxW). 

Additionally, along the course of this project an extensive population genetics study will be conducted on *Hillebrandia* to assess essential traits as mating system, population structure, and relatedness, which are essential for conservation genomics assessments. This study will thus provide information to re-evaluate the conservation status of *Hillebrandia* and several *Begonia* clades, and valuable tools for potential genetic rescue efforts, paving the way for future conservation genomics projects.

### **Vision and approach**

We propose to investigate this important evolutionary question using pre-existing high quality chromosome-scale reference genomes and haplotype-resolved NGS data sets. To recover the specimens necessary to develop this approach, we will organise an expedition to the Hawaiian archipelago to collect *Hillebrandia* specimens from populations along the Northern coast of Kauai, as well as on Molokai and Maui islands, supported by the NTBG. *Begonia* specimens required for molecular work will be sourced from the living collections of RBGE and the Botanical Garden of Lyon. For the deleterious alleles study, one *Begonia* specimen per species and one *Hillebrandia* specimen per population will be sequenced using WGS Illumina technology. In addition, ten individuals of each *Hillebrandia* population will be sequenced using Illumina technology with a target capture method for population genetic studies. To improve the reference genomes, one specimen of *Begonia* from each geographically circumscribed clade (Asian, Neotropical, African) and one specimen of *Hillebrandia* might be sequenced with PacBio HiFi long-reads technology.

# **Anticipated results**

Three publications are to be expected, one on the genetic basis of diversification and endemism in *Begoniaceae*, another on the evolutionary history of *Hillebrandia* on the Hawaiian Islands, and a final one on the conservation status of *Hillebrandia* and strategies of genetic rescue.

For each population sampled in Hawaii, we will prepare herbarium specimens for the NTBG and the RBGE, thereby enhancing the collections of both institutions. Additionally, we will expand the diversity of the *Hillebrandia* living collections at NTBG and RBGE by introducing more genotypes. This effort will increase the genetic diversity of the collections, improving their resilience and long-term survival.

The genomic resources produced within the project will be accessible by IEG for further studies on the *Begoniaceae* biodiversity, genome evolution, and functional studies, reinforcing international collaborations with stakeholders and potential future partners working on the same model as the Key Laboratory of Southern Subtropical Plant Diversity, Chinese Academy of Sciences, China or the Research Museum and Herbarium (HAST), Academia Sinica, Taiwan.   
Beyond this model group, the genetic basis of diversity or extinction identified in *Begoniaceae* will be applied to future studies of other plant groups. This will allow for comparisons to determine whether similar patterns emerge or if the scenarios of diversification are more complex. These findings will encourage deeper exploration into the broader questions of what drives species success or extinction.
